Ignore Test Failures (Optional):
--------------------------------

By default:

✔ All Tests Pass  -> BUILD SUCCESS
✘ Any Test Fails -> BUILD FAILURE

If you want Maven to continue the build even when test cases fail,
add the following configuration inside Maven Surefire Plugin:

<plugin>
    <groupId>org.apache.maven.plugins</groupId>
    <artifactId>maven-surefire-plugin</artifactId>
    <version>3.2.2</version>

    <configuration>
        <suiteXmlFiles>
            <suiteXmlFile>master.xml</suiteXmlFile>
        </suiteXmlFiles>

        <testFailureIgnore>true</testFailureIgnore>

    </configuration>
</plugin>

Result:

Tests run: 10
Failures: 2
Errors: 0
Skipped: 0

BUILD SUCCESS

Interview Answer:

By default, Maven marks the build as FAILED if any test case fails.
Using:

<testFailureIgnore>true</testFailureIgnore>

in the Maven Surefire Plugin instructs Maven to continue the build
and show BUILD SUCCESS even when some test cases fail.

Note:
This configuration is generally NOT recommended in automation
frameworks and CI/CD pipelines because failed test cases should
normally fail the build and notify the team.

Interview Question:
Can you explain Maven and Maven Build Lifecycle?

Answer:

Maven is a Build Automation and Dependency Management Tool used primarily for Java projects.

It helps us to:

1. Manage project dependencies.
2. Compile source code.
3. Execute test cases.
4. Create build artifacts such as JAR/WAR files.
5. Install artifacts into local repositories.
6. Deploy artifacts to remote repositories.

Maven uses a configuration file called pom.xml
(Project Object Model) where we define:

- Project information
- Dependencies
- Plugins
- Build configurations

For example:
- Selenium dependency
- TestNG dependency
- Maven Surefire Plugin
- Maven Compiler Plugin

------------------------------------------------------------

Maven Build Lifecycle:

Maven follows a predefined lifecycle called the Default Build Lifecycle.

validate
    ↓
compile
    ↓
test
    ↓
package
    ↓
verify
    ↓
install
    ↓
deploy

1. validate
   - Validates project structure and pom.xml.

2. compile
   - Compiles source code.
   - Converts .java files into .class files.

3. test
   - Compiles test classes.
   - Executes TestNG/JUnit test cases.

4. package
   - Creates JAR/WAR file.

5. verify
   - Performs additional quality checks.

6. install
   - Installs the artifact into the local Maven repository (.m2).

7. deploy
   - Uploads the artifact to a remote repository such as Nexus or Artifactory.

------------------------------------------------------------

